[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Every file tool you reach for online, the PDF merger, the image converter, the video trimmer, the background remover, quietly uploads your files to somebody else\'s server. Snap outer flips that. It\'s a self-hosted toolkit with 157 tools across images, video, audio, PDFs,'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'and files, and not a single byte leaves your machine. It\'s completely free and fully offline. There\'s one catch I\'ll get to before the end, but first, watch the whole thing run from a phone. Here\'s'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Snap outer site pulled up on a phone, and the headline is the entire pitch in five words: Nothing leaves your network. Scroll down, and the toolkit is laid out by category, clean and tap friendly. Image tools, 64 of them. Video, 29.'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Audio, 17. PDFs and documents, 25. File converters, 22. Tap any card and you\'re resizing, converting, compressing, or transcribing right there in the browser,'

[00:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'processed on your own hardware. No account, no upload, no waiting on someone\'s free tier, no daily limit nudging you toward a subscription. The interface speaks 21 languages with full right-to-left support, so it\'s not'

[01:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'just an English-only project. And it runs anywhere, from a beefy workstation down to a Raspberry Pi sitting in a closet. The fact that the whole thing is this usable on a small phone screen tells you the front end was actually'

[01:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'thought through. Snap outer comes from a small team led by Siddharth Kumar Saw, building out of Singapore. It\'s only about 3 months old on GitHub, and it\'s already pulled 1,390 stars, which usually means people were waiting'

[01:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'for exactly this. And it\'s not a weekend toy. New releases land every couple of weeks. It carries the OpenSSF best practices badge for security hygiene, and there\'s an active Discord and issue tracker'

[01:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'behind it. The code base is TypeScript, the work is steady, and the road map is public. Version 2.0 is already in the pipeline. When you\'re going to point a tool at your private document, that kind of'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'momentum and transparency is exactly what you want to see before you trust it. Let\'s sit on that number for a second because it\'s the whole story. 157 tools. Not 157 buttons that secretly phone a cloud API. 157 real processing'

[02:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'tools running locally on your own box. Picture how many random sites you\'d normally bounce through to get through a single day. One to merge PDFs, one to compress a video, one to strip a'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'background, one to convert that HEIC photo your phone insists on shooting. Every one of those is a stranger\'s server quietly seeing your files. Snap Auto folds all of it into one app you control, and it goes further than a flat'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'list of tools. You can chain steps into reusable pipelines. Say, resize, watermark, then compress. Export that workflow as JSON and batch it across unlimited files at once. One number, but'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'a lot of leverage hiding behind it. Here\'s how those 157 break down. Image tools lead the pack at 64. Resize, crop, convert, watermark, even vectorize. Plus a full layer-based editor with brushes,'

[02:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'curves, and filters that runs right in the browser. It reads 55 plus input formats, including 23 camera raw formats. So, the files straight off your camera just work. Video is next with 29. Trim, compress,'

[03:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'stabilize, change frame rate, turn clips into GIFs, burn or extract subtitles. PDFs and documents bring 25. Merge, split, redact, OCR, and convert to and from Word, Excel, and PowerPoint. File'

[03:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'converters add 22 for CSV, JSON, XML, and YAML wrangling. Even a quick chart maker. And audio rounds it out with 17 for normalizing, noise reduction, silence trimming, and pitch shifting.'

[03:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Whatever you were about to Google a converter for, it\'s probably already in here. Here\'s the part that surprised me. Snap Auto ships local AI, and I mean genuinely local. Running on your own hardware with no internet connection at'

[03:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'all. It\'ll remove backgrounds, upscale low-res images, restore and colorize old photos, erase unwanted objects, blur faces for privacy, and even expand a canvas beyond its original edges.'

[04:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'It pulls text straight out of images and PDFs with OCR. Transcribes audio and auto generates subtitles for your videos. That\'s the exact category of work you\'d normally hand to a paid cloud service.'

[04:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'And to do it, you\'d be uploading your private photos and recordings to someone else\'s GPU. Here, none of it leaves the room. And if you\'re plugging Snapdrop into a bigger setup, it supports OIDC single sign-on, so you can log in with'

[04:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'Google, GitHub, Okta, or any OpenID provider, and every tool is reachable through a REST API with an API key. So, here\'s the catch I promised, and it\'s an honest one. Snapdrop is dual licensed.'

[04:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'For you self-hosting it at home or for your own team, it\'s free and open source under the AGPLv3. Use it, modify it, run it forever. No payment, no phone home. But, the AGPL'

[04:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'has teeth, and you should understand them. If you build Snapdrop into a product or a hosted service that other people use over a network, that license obligates you to share your source code with those users. If you\'d rather wrap'

[05:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'it into a closed, proprietary, or commercial offering without that obligation, the maintainers sell a separate commercial license, and you contact them for terms. For the vast majority of people watching, the home lab crowd, the'

[05:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'privacy conscious, anyone just processing their own files, that copyleft clause simply never triggers. It\'s only a factor if you\'re turning it into something you sell. Know the rule going in, and there are no surprises'

[05:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'later. Getting it running is genuinely a one-stack job, and there\'s no SaaS account anywhere in the picture. Snapdrop is a small Docker Compose stack. The app, Postgres 17, and Redis 8 wired together with one file. Drop in'

[05:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'that Compose file, run Docker Compose up, and a minute later, you\'ve got the full toolkit waiting on port 1349. No external dependencies, nothing reaching out to the cloud, just three containers on your own box. It\'s'

[06:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'multi-arch out of the box, so the exact same setup works on an Intel server, Apple Silicon, or an ARM Raspberry Pi humming away in the corner. Point a volume at it for persistent storage, And because there\'s a REST API with an'

[06:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'interactive docs page, every one of those 157 tools is scriptable, not just clickable. Wire it into your own automations and cron jobs. Your files, your hardware, your rules. So, that\'s Snap Otter. 157 file tools, real local'

[06:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'AI, reusable pipelines, an SSO ready API, and the whole thing fully self-hosted, so your files never leave your network. If you\'re tired of feeding personal'

[06:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'documents into random converter sites, this is the one to spin up this weekend. The maintainers even host a live demo if you want to poke at it before you commit. The repository and that demo are linked in the description. If this was useful, do me a favor and subscribe. We dig up a'

[06:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'fresh open source tool every single week. I\'ll see you in the next one.'
